1.	Introduction 

On a global scale, international student mobility has become an essential phenomenon in modern higher education, indicating the development speed of globalisation and the increased interconnectivity of institutional systems. The transnational migration of students for tertiary education has grown at an exponential rate in the last two decades so that global enrollment figures have reached unprecedented heights.    
Such mobility is driven by a complex nexus of factors that include a desire for a good education, opportunities to build a career, the opportunity to experience other cultures, and the aspiration to develop personally. As states compete to attract international talent, understanding decision-making processes and motivational antecedents that guide the choices of students in terms of where to go to school assumes renewed significance for policy makers, academic institutions and academics.  
India has become one of the largest source countries of international students in the world and in the process, is making a significant contribution to global student mobility flows. Driven by a rapidly growing middle class, increasing expectations for world-class education and perceived limitations in the domestic higher education capacity and quality, hundreds of thousands of Indian students pursue studies abroad each year in pursuit of undergraduate and postgraduate degrees. 
Historically, Indian students were stick to the Anglophone destinations, including the United States, the United Kingdom, Canada and Australia, due to prestige of the institutions, English language courses and established dispersion. In recent years, however, a noticeable diversification in the choice of destinations has been observed with European countries, especially those with affordable, good quality education, gaining ground among the Indian students.  
The Czech Republic is a part of the emerging and increasingly attractive destination in the changing world of international student mobility. Located at the heart of Central Europe, the Czech Republic offers a unique combination of characteristics that sets it apart from the traditional places of study. The nation is blessed with a well-founded higher education system of a number of historically important universities that are gaining an ever-growing international reputation. Universities within the Czech Republic do provide programmes taught in English in a range of fields, focusing especially on medicine and engineering, business and natural sciences.  
Additionally, the cost of education and the cost of living in the Czech Republic is significantly less than that in Western European countries and English-speaking countries, thus making it an economically best option for middle class families in India. Students have access to travel, cultural exchange, and potential employment prospects in the larger European market due to the country's strategic location inside the European Union.   
Moreover, the Czech Republic's high standard of living, rich cultural legacy, and generally safe climate make it a desirable location for academic study. Despite the growing number of Indian students in the Czech higher education institutions, there is still a considerable gap in the empirical knowledge of the determinants shaping the choice of destination. Existing scholarship offers a wealth of information regarding Indian student mobility to traditional host nations, as well as information on generally applicable factors that affect international student decision processes.  
However, there hasn't been much academic research on the precise rationale behind Indian students' preference for the Czech Republic over other options. The nation is a non-Anglophone, unique travel destination that faces competition from both leading Western universities and emerging European rivals, making this drawback particularly crucial. An explanation of the motivations, expectations, and decision-making processes of Indian students choosing the Czech Republic is of great importance for a number of stakeholders, including Czech universities trying to improve their recruitment strategies, Indian educational counsellors advising prospective students, policymakers in both countries hoping to enhance educational ties, and applicants who stand to gain from an evidence-based understanding of peer experiences and the factors that influence choices.  
The importance of this analysis goes beyond simply academic interest and has vital contributions to make to the field of international student mobility research.  
Firstly, by examining the destination choice from the point of view of Self-Determination Theory, which emphasises intrinsic motivation, autonomy, competence, and relatedness of human behaviour, it mainly advances theoretical understanding. This framework offers a thorough explanation of how practical factors and psychological needs interact to influence decisions about educational migration.        
Secondly, the study contributes to the practical need for evidence-based insights that can be incorporated into institutional strategies, marketing campaigns, and policy interventions with the goal of attracting and assisting Indian students in the Czech Republic.   
Thirdly, the research contributes to broader discussions regarding the diversification of international student flows and shifts in international higher education markets by focusing on an emerging destination.   
In the end, the results may have an impact on how geographical patterns of educational mobility are understood, as well as how non-traditional destinations help students from developing economies find accessible routes to international education.  
This dissertation is a systematic study, which examines the factors that affect the decision of Indian students to study for a higher education in the Czech Republic.  By using a quantitative survey methodology within the framework of the Self-Determination Theory and informed by an extensive review of the scholarly literature on student mobility, this study seeks to identify and assess the academic, financial, cultural, social and psychological factors affecting destination choice.  
 The empirical focus herein is narrowed down to Indian university students who are enrolled within Czech institutions and accordingly being able to capture in depth the lived experience, motivation drivers and perceptual construct of the students. Through this investigation, the study aims to contribute to the existing knowledge gap and provide practical information that may contribute to crafting policies that may lead to the Czech Republic's position as a favourable destination for Indian students seeking high quality, affordable and enriching international educational experiences.  
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
2. Objective and Methodology  
2.1 Objectives  
The current study will lead to answer the following Research Question: 
What are the key economic, psychological, and socio-cultural factors influencing Indian students’ decision to pursue higher education in the Czech Republic? 
To attain the answer to the question, focus is set on the following objectives that will be accessed to understand the influencing factors. 
1.	Analysing which economic factors such as tuition costs, cost of living, availability of scholarship and employment opportunities, attracts Indian students to Czech Republic. 
2.	To evaluate the psychological drivers namely the independence, self-growth, career progression, and avoid domestic ambiguities, which drive Indian students to pursue higher education in the Czech Republic. 
3.	Current live experiences of Indian students in the Czech Republic links to level of safety, affordability, and career opportunities along with work rights affect the choice of students who may choose to stay in the Czech Republic after graduation 
4.	The analysis of the demographic factors such as age, gender, level of degree, and the year of admission, is associated with the key motivation factors that drive students into studying in the Czech Republic. 
 
2.2 Hypotheses: 
By keeping objectives in frame, there must be some factors which can prove the bases of this research by their hypotheses.  
Hypothesis 1: Male and female Indian students have significantly different monthly expenditures. 
Hypothesis 2: Master’s level students have a significantly higher average monthly expenditure than bachelor’s level students. 
Hypothesis 3: Choice of institution significantly impacts a student's monthly expenditure. 
Hypothesis 4: Expenditure levels differ significantly between students who perceive high safety versus those who perceive low/moderate safety. 
Hypothesis 5: Students for whom affordability was a primary factor spend significantly different amounts on rent. 
Hypothesis 6: Gender significantly influences how Indian students manage their living expenses, suggesting a measurable difference between male and female. 
These hypotheses are then tested thoroughly by analysing data to see whether the result are actually significant.  
 
2.3 Methodology 
In this section, the methods through which this research is carried out and what technique or process we perform to gather data for further analysis:  
2.3.1 Data Collection 
The study employs quantitative research by utilizing a cross-sectional survey methodology. With the main aim of establishing patterns, relationships, and trends of the motivational profile of Indian students studying in the Czech Republic, it is exploratory and detailed. Further, the theoretical background of the research is Self-Determination Theory (SDT), which distinguishes between intrinsic (personal development, intellectual or academic interests and autonomy) and extrinsic motivators (financial gains, degree recognition, and job opportunities). 
2.3.1.1 Population and sampling 
 
•	Target population: The target group are the currently enrolled Indian students in the higher education universities in the Czech Republic and the university graduate students working in the country. The time frame of the research includes students who came to 2015-2025 to get wider understanding of the factors. During this decade, multiple changes happened in the world and in Czech Republic. Hence, it’s easy to find out if the factors are the same or not. • Sampling Technique:  The google link has been distributed to different channels: 
I.	Student associations: Distributed to Indian student community and cultural group organizations in Czech Republic like Studyin.cz 
II.	Social Media Platforms: Posting the survey link to relevant WhatsApp group, Facebook group, LinkedIn communities. 
III.	Printing and pasting QR copies in Dormitories and University boards. 
IV.	Snowball Sampling: Encouraging participants to share the survey with peers.             
 
•	Sample Size: The study aimed to attain at least 150-200 respondents where 178 respondents were finally received. The sample consists of students who are chosen as the reflection of the groups of different academic degrees, such as Bachelor, Master, Doctoral, and Postdoctoral, and who represent various age groups (18 to 40 years old). 
 
•	Participation Requirements:  
-	Indian Nationals 
-	Currently enrolled or graduated students from Czech Universities  
-	Arrived in year 2015 to 2025 
•	Limitations of Participants: 
-	Students who left the Czech Republic permanently. 
-	Students enrolled in short term courses like Erasmus or exchange. 
-	Never had Student visa. 
2.3.2 Survey Questionnaire 
A constructed, structured and self-administered questionnaire has been developed completely anonymously and distributed through Google Forms Online. This tool consists of items that are closed-ended only and most of the items have Likert- scales to measure the relative importance of various motivational antecedents. The questionnaire has been designed in such a way that it divides the information into several dimensions: 
 
• Section A: Demographic Information 
-	Age, Gender, Email address – Optional 
-	Current Status – Studying, Studying and Working, Graduated and Working, Other 
-	Year of Arrival in Czech Republic 
-	Name of University enrolled in 
-	Level of Degree enrolled in 
-	Medium of Instruction (English, Czech taught, other) 
•	Section B: Motivational Factors for staying Czech Republic: 
Rate the Importance from Extremely Important to Not Important 
-	Low tuition fees 
-	Affordability in living cost 
-	Scholarship Availability 
-	English Taught programs 
-	Global recognition of degree 
•	Section C: Motivational Factors for staying Czech Republic: 
Rate the Importance from Extremely Important to Not Important 
-	Safety and Low crime rate 
-	Post Study work options/rights 
-	Location in Europe/Travel opportunities 
-	Ease student visa 
-	Presence of Indian community 
• Section D: Living Experience and Employment 
-	Perception of Safety in the Czech Republic (Subjective answer) 
-	Assessment of cost of living (Affordable, manageable but rising, too expensive) 
