The data was gathered over a period of 5 weeks to enable adequate response rates. The response was voluntary and the respondents were guaranteed confidentiality and anonymity in the beginning.  The survey was done with informed consent. 
2.3.3 Data Analysis Strategy 
As mentioned above, the data collected from the online survey was exported, cleaned, and analysed using descriptive statistics via spreadsheet software. The primary aim of this research is exploratory and descriptive and to follow that, Frequency distributions, percentages, and mean scores were calculated and visually represented through bar charts and pie charts to identify overarching trends has been used. To explore the economic and demographic aspects of the study, the analysis looked at practical pull factors like tuition costs, living expenses, job opportunities, and scholarship availability as external motivators. Basic cross-tabulation was used to link demographic variables, such as age, gender, degree level, and admission year, with these main motivational factors. This showed how various student groups prioritized their practical needs. 
More importantly, the analytical framework was based on Self-Determination Theory (SDT) to understand the psychological reasons behind destination choice and post-graduation plans. Survey responses were directly connected to SDT’s main intrinsic psychological needs: Autonomy, which is the desire for independence and avoiding domestic uncertainties; Competence, which drives personal growth, career advancement, and academic quality; and Relatedness, which involves feeling secure, safe, and connected in the host country. By examining the average importance scores and responses related to these psychological factors, the analysis evaluated how meeting these needs, along with current experiences like affordability, safety, and work rights, influenced the students' initial motivations and their later decisions to stay in the Czech Republic after graduation. 
3. Literature Review   
3.1 Theoretical Frameworks for International Student Mobility   
The phenomenon of international student mobility is complex. Researchers have looked at it from various angles, and each viewpoint offers different insights into why students decide to study abroad, how they make those decisions, and the effects of their choices. Self-determination theory and the Push-Pull Model are two theoretical models, in particular, that are relevant in explaining the factors that determine the destination choices of students. These models offer parallel positions whereby one is focused on the psychological factors behind motivation and the other the situational forces that lead and entice student mobility. Together, they provide a general basis of the analysis of the reasons why Indian students choose the Czech Republic as a study destination.  
3.1.1 Chapter of level 3 
Self-Determination Theory (SDT) developed by Deci and Ryan [31] is a general theoretical framework of human motivation, which has been implemented widely in various fields of activity, such as education, health, workplace, and sport. Its core is that SDT assumes that people have inherent psychological needs, the satisfaction of which promotes optimal functioning, wellbeing, and intrinsic motivation. The theory outlines three fundamental needs, namely autonomy, the necessity to feel that one is in control of his or her behaviour and that it is self-perceived and self-endorsed; competence, the need to feel capable of bringing desired results and of using his or her abilities; and relatedness, the necessity to feel that he or she has a connection with others, cares about them and is cared about, and belongs. SDT also differentiates between the different types of motivation on a continuum of amotivation, which implies the lack of intentionality, and different types of extrinsic motivation, which assume acting to achieve separable outcomes and finally intrinsic motivation, which implies engagement due to inherent contentment with the activity itself.   
Self-Determination Theory provides a sound conceptual framework in explaining the motivational mechanism that situates the choice of students to avail themselves with the opportunity of studying overseas and the choice of specific destinations in the case of international student mobility [31]. Available empirical studies which have utilised SDT in the context of international education reveal that students who choose to study abroad due to autonomous reasons i.e. an intrinsic interest in an object, personal values, and self-endorsed goals tend to be more satisfied, perform better academically and have better well-being as compared to those whose study-abroad decisions are based on controlled extrinsic reasons i.e. parental pressure or societal expectations. An integrative approach to the question of international students’ motivation to study abroad was investigated by Yue and colleagues who applied Expectancy-Value Theory and Self-Determination Theory simultaneously, and found out that both intrinsic motivation and satisfaction of the initial needs of a person were strong predictors of motivation to study abroad and further experience . This literature thus indicates the extreme importance of understanding not only the external factors which propel students towards certain destinations but also the internal motivational nature which can lead students to view themselves as having an autonomous choice as it can be in accordance with their true interests and values [4].   
The dimension of autonomy of Self-Determination Theory (SDT) is especially relevant to explain the destination choice of international students. Learners might experience a destination to provide more freedom of choice of courses and independent research, self-directed learning, and enforcing personal lifestyle choices, which are likely to make this destination more appealing to the learner. In the case of Indian students, who often have to struggle with complex family demands and social pressure on academic and career paths, the ability to exercise free will in a new cultural context can be an important pull factor. With a relatively flexible system of higher education and being in a tradition of European student-centred learning, the Czech Republic might therefore be attractive to students who want greater autonomy as compared to more constraining or prescriptive learning environments.  [31] 
The second pillar of the Self-Determination Theory (SDT) is competence, which deals with the perceptions of students regarding the likelihood of a potential study destination to help them achieve their selves through development of abilities, academic success, and enhancement of professional talents. The students are therefore predisposed to gravitate towards the destinations that they consider to be friendly to their academic thriving, acquisition of substantive knowledge and credentials as well as development of competency that will help them in their further professional activities. Empirical research studies indicate that perceptions about the quality of learning, prestige of the school, and access to learning resources and support facilities all have a cumulative effect on the sense of competence derivation in students in a particular environment. [7],[22] Regarding Indian students who are considering the Czech Republic, such variables as the quality of academic programmes, the reputation of the Czech universities in a certain field (particularly medicine and engineering), and the availability of research opportunities can be evaluated in terms of the analytic perspective of competence development.   
The third basic need that has been established in Self-Determination Theory (SDT) is called relatedness and explains the importance of being socially connected and having the sense of belonging. International students are faced with the challenge of forming new social networks under cultural milieu that are often located miles apart and unrelated to the family and support systems that have been formed. Places that are perceived to be warm, safe and supporting development of substantive interpersonal relationships are seen as being more attractive. The availability of an existing Indian community of students, the hospitality of the local communities, international exchange opportunities, and institutional provisions of international students all help to ease the relatedness needs. The role of social integration and support networks in influencing general satisfaction and academic achievements in international students is always emphasised in empirical research studies on the subject. A study in which the intentions of participants in the Erasmus+ programme were surveyed in terms of SDT demonstrated that needs associated with relatedness, in particular the need to connect with people and have cultural experiences, served as strong motivational factors in participating in the study abroad programmes. [27].   
A few empirical studies have used Self-Determination Theory to provide an examination on the motivation of international students and their choice of destination. On the theoretical framework of SDT, King and co-researchers discussed the importance of stimulation of intrinsic motivations in studying abroad by the allure of a destination. Their empirical research, performed by working with educational travelers in Paris, proved that destination appeal mediates the relationship between the context variables and intrinsic motivation, which presupposes that the role of destinations in enhancing autonomous decision-making of students can be achieved by providing information and minimising external control [29]. This finding has a major implication on understanding how the Czech Republic would place itself to appeal to intrinsically motivated Indian students.    
A different study by Muthuswamy and his colleagues has investigated the effect of self-determined motivation, and the goal orientations of international students on subjective wellbeing with goal satisfaction of psychological needs as mediating variable [28]. Though the particular population of the Indian learners or learners in the Czech Republic was not the target of this research, the outcome of this research shows that in the host setting when the primary psychological needs of the students are met, their self-determined motivation is linked with the increased well-being and general satisfaction. Therefore, the policy makers and universities in Czech need not merely focus on practical factors like tuition fees and the availability of programmes but also to create settings that can enable autonomy, competency, and relatedness of international students.   
The Self-Determination Theory applied to international student mobility requires a good distinction between autonomous and controlled motivation.  
Autonomous motivation is characterised by inherent motives to study abroad because of pure enjoyment and interest as well as well-assimilated extrinsic motives, when the activity of studying abroad is among the values and the long-term goals of an individual. In comparison, the controlled motivation is brought about by an outside force or the contingent reward or the internal drive like feeling guilty or anxious that drives to act. Empirical evidence has continually shown that autonomous motivation is associated with better academic perseverance, greater performance and better psychological health. In case with Indian students, the ability to identify whether the choice to study in the Czech Republic is individual or it is caused by external factors like parental demands or limited opportunities in the native country can reveal the anticipated level of satisfaction and academic performance [4], [31].   
The criticisms about the use of Self-Determination Theory in cross-cultural contexts have preempted questions about whether the three basic psychological needs postulated by the theory are universal or cultural-specific. Empirical studies suggest that the relative prominence of autonomy, competence and relatedness can, in turn, differ between cultural milieus; collectivist societies, in particular, are observed to assign higher levels of prominence to relatedness and smaller levels of prominence to autonomy compared to individualist societies[34],[35].  Although there is diversity, existing cross-cultural theory shows that these needs are mostly universal. At the same time, it recognizes that their expression and satisfaction can vary by culture. For Indian students, who come from a family-focused background where interdependence and group decision-making are often prioritized, the relationship between autonomy and relatedness is particularly complex. This intricacy explorations of how the notions of autonomy and relatedness experience the process of coming together with this demographic not only thought-provoking but also empirically necessary.   
Overall, the Self-Determination Theory offers a very insightful and detailed model when it comes to explaining the psychological decision-making that guides the selection of the Czech Republic as a study destination among Indian students. Exploring the perception of the Czech Republic in terms of autonomy, competence, and relatedness appeal, and differentiating among autonomous and controlled types of motivation, the researchers and practitioners are likely to get a better understanding of what is appealing to the Indian students in terms of this destination and how their experiences can be facilitated in order to meet their psychological needs and general well-being.  [34],[35] 

 3.1.2. Push-Pull Model in Student Mobility   
Building on the Push–Pull framework discussed earlier, the Push-Pull Model still is among the most used frameworks to explain the international mobility of students, which assumes that migration decisions are predetermined by a complex of the structural factors in the country of origin (push factors) and positive features of the country of destination (pull factors). 
Push factors in the Indian context entail restricted ability of the top institutions, high competition to join an institution, perceived inequality in the quality of education and limited availability of professional opportunities in some areas. Such structural constraints prompt students to seek other avenues of academic and career development by studying abroad. 
On the other hand, Czech Republic has some pull factors that are identifiable. These comprise relatively low tuition fees, reduced cost of living as compared to the Anglophone places of choice, the presence of English based programmes, recognised European degrees through the Bologna regime, and its strategic location in the European Union. Also, the image of safety, political stability, and the existence of the developing Indian student community makes it more attractive. 
Nevertheless, although the Push-Pull Model is useful in classifying structural determinants, the model has been faulted because it simplifies decision-making among students. Students do not receive what is imposed upon them but are proactive and mediated in their decisions by aspirations, social networks, and psychological forces. Because of this reason, the Push-Pull Model is most analytical in combination with models of motivation like Self-Determination Theory, which elucidates the interaction of structural influences with internal psychological requirements. 
Therefore, when Indian students select the Czech Republic, push factors will form the initial drive in the outward mobility, and the destination selection will be created by the pull factors. The outcome of the decision-making occurs between these situational forces and personal motivational orientations. 
[4], [31] 
3.2 Factors Influencing Study Abroad Destination Choice    
The choice in favour of studying abroad and the choice of a specific country of study depends on a complex of factors that may be grouped into the academic, economic, cultural-social and psychological aspects. Such variables neither work alone, but they interrelate in complex ways, and each of them presupposes various degrees of salience of individual students based on their circumstances, priorities, and values. A thorough explanation of these variables and their relative significance is necessary to explain the choice of the Indian students to the Czech Republic, and to come up with measures that can help make the destination more appealing and the support systems more powerful. [7], [13], [18]  
3.2.1. Academic Factors   
The academic factors are always present in literature as one of the most salient aspects of international students’ destination choice. These aspects include the standard of education, access to and applicability of degree courses, reputation of the institution, research facilities and the foreign acceptability of degrees. To students who put so much time, money, and effort in international education, academic qualifications and learning experiences that they expect to attain are the most important considerations[22].   
Curriculum rigor, pedagogical practices, learning materials, faculty credentials, student/faculty ratios, and the general standards of academic work are multidimensional constructs that make up the quality of education. Students want to visit places where they believe they will get high quality teaching which will provide them with knowledge, skills and competencies that are worth being in the global labor market. Gurucharan et al. (2019) used Fuzzy Analytical  
Hierarchical Process to priorities the determinants of international education destination among Indian students and listed the aspects of academic factors as one of the highest priorities, especially quality and reputation of educational institutions [7]. This observation is consistent with the general findings of other studies that have examined the mobility of international students and which have established that the perceived educational quality is one of the major attractors. [22]  
Availability of given academic programmes is another critical factor in selection of destinations to study. They are bound to be attracted to the areas that can provide them with the curricula that will support their academic activities and career goals. Medicine, engineering, business administration, computer science and natural sciences are some of the fields that are very popular among the Indian students especially. Czech Republic has developed skills in some of these areas, with the medical schools especially appealing to Indian students. Czech medical schools also offer English-taught MD programmes which are internationally recognized and allow licensure in a variety of jurisdictions. The contrast between such offerings with relatively lower tuition rates in comparison with Western medical training makes the Czech Republic a great option of future doctors who were born in India. [10], [16], [14]  
The institutional standing has a strong impact on the preferences of the destinations. Students and their families use university rankings, accreditation status and historical prestige to judge prospective hosts. Although Czech universities do not play as high profile in the international ranking as those in the United States or the United Kingdom, several Czech universities have strong regional reputations and well-established histories. Charles University, Czech Technical University, Masaryk University among others are recognized to make contributions to academics and therefore attract international enrolment. To Indian scholars, the reputation of the particular programme or department can be considered more significant than the overall rankings of universities particularly in specialized areas. [7], [22] 
Academic credentials are an important consideration which guarantee international recognition and mobility of the same. Students want to be sure that their qualifications will be recognised and that it will be appreciated not only in the host country but also in their home country and other jurisdictions where the students may seek employment. Students of the Czech Republic (and their degrees, especially those of reputable universities) are usually recognised throughout the European Union by the Bologna Process and the European Credit Transfer and Accumulation System. The validation of the Czech degree by the Indian authorities, both within and outside the country is a critical consideration to the Indian students. Empirical research on the preferences of Indian students towards studying abroad has shown that concerns over degree recognition and accreditation have a great impact on destination choice with the students preferring those places whose degrees are well established and generally recognized. [10].   
The ability to use faculty knowledge and available research opportunities is of utmost importance to graduate students and those who are enrolled in research-based programmes. Proximity to superior researchers, state of the art laboratories and the likelihood of contributing to state-of-the-art studies are very strong lures. The Czech universities in the research field show strong capacities in the spectrum 
of the research field, and the active participation of the country in European research networks and funding mechanisms, including Horizon Europe, gives Czech students a chance to be involved in the international joint research projects. To Indian students who have chosen the research career, these opportunities are even more alluring, especially when considered in take with the relatively cheaper cost of living, as compared to Western Europe [16].   
Language of instruction is a notable academic predictor of choice of destination in the study abroad. In the case of Indian learners, whose primary or secondary schooling is mostly conducted in English, the accessibility is critically determined by the provision of English-taught curricula. The Czech Republic has adjusted to the international demand through increasing the number of English based programmes at the master’s and doctorate levels in a variety of fields. Such development makes the Czech institutions more appropriate to Indian students who do not understand Czech. However, the differences in calibre and access to English-taught courses by different universities and disciplines might influence enrolment choices [13], [18].   
There is also influence of pedagogical methodologies. Students are attracted to those destinations which teaching methods are in line with their epistemic preferences and professional growth needs. Czech universities, which are a typical example of European institutions of higher learning, tend to anticipate critical inquiry, independent research and learner-based approaches to education, unlike the examination-based modalities of some Indian contexts. Such methodological deviations can be of special interest to the students who focus on the development of autonomy and competence as these concepts are conceptualized in the Self Determination Theory[4], [31] .   
The use of academic determinants in the selection of study-abroad is always emphasized by empirical literature. The study by Singh and colleagues determined that academic reputation and quality of the programmes are the most important in destination preferences of Indian business school students. Similarly, the study of motivational inclinations of international students, which occurs within the context of Expectancy Theory and Self-Determination Theory, found that academic expectations and value of educational outcomes is a significantly strong predictor of the intentions of study-abroad. The findings support the idea that, despite the power of financial, cultural, and other auxiliary factors, academic factors are critical in the decision process of most students [13], [4].   
Within the framework of the Czech Republic, to increase academic appeal, it is required to not only maintain but also to improve the level of instruction and successfully transfer this excellence to the potential Indian students. Specific outreach, reinforcement of curricular advantages, academic scholarship, research opportunities, graduate paths, and international certifications can bring Czech universities to the academic credibility level as an alternative.  
Furthermore, official partnerships with Indian organisations, participation in educational fairs in India as well as communication with academic consultants can be used to increase the knowledge about Czech higher-education opportunities among Indian students and their circles [16].   
3.2.2. Financial Factors   
One of the most salient as well as often decisive factors affecting the choice of destination by international students is the financial factor. The external cost of studying overseas is a significant investment to both the students and their families which includes the cost of tuition fees, cost of living, cost of travelling, cost of health insurance fees as well as other cost bones. To many Indian families, especially those in the middle-class bracket it is a financial strain, which involves a lot of careful budgeting, restrained savings building, and even borrowing of loan facilities to send one of their children abroad to pursue higher education. Thus, the relative price of a host country in comparison to the perceived standard and value of the educational product is a decisive factor of the student selection [7], [15], [16].  
There is a lot of variation in tuition fees depending on the destination and institutions. Conventional places like the United States and the United Kingdom are characterised by high tuition fees particularly among international scholars who are supposed to pay higher fees compared to their native colleagues. Conversely, several European jurisdictions such as Czech Republic offer relatively low-priced tuition models, most especially state universities. The tuition fees of English-taught programmes in the Czech Republic are relatively affordable when compared to those that exist in the 
Western European region and are significantly lower in comparison with the Anglophone destinations [13]. To give an example, annual enrolment fees at English-taught programmes in Czech state universities are generally between approx. 48.969.40 CZK to 367,270.50 CZK(€2,000 to €15,000), depending on the course and the level of study, unlike in the United Kingdom 367,270.50 CZK to 73.4541.00 (between €15,000 and €30,000) and in the United States 422 984,00 CZK to 1057460.00 CZK (between $20,000 and $50,000) [7]. This high-cost difference makes the Czech Republic a good alternative to the Indian students who want to pursue education in Europe at affordable cost.  
Another key financial factor is the cost of living. This group includes housing, food, transportation, energy and personal spending. The Czech nation, specifically, in the places beyond Prague, has a comparably low cost of living when compared to the Western European countries. Students can afford affordable housing and other day-to-day costs on food and transportation are moderate. Comparative research of student experiences among the European destinations has recorded that the Central and Eastern European countries tend to offer cheaper living costs, which forms a strong pull factor among international students who have their origin in the developing countries.[18] The promise of living a comfortable life at a small budget, as Indian students would do, and getting quality education in the Czech Republic is a significant positive attribute of the country to them.[3][8]  
The allowance of scholarships, grants, and other financial aid has the potential to have a significant impact on destination choice due to the ability to reduce the fiscal load. Although the Czech Republic does not offer international students such comprehensive scholarship programmes as in other countries, there are opportunities offered through Czech government scholarship schemes, institutional awards and European Union programmes. Moreover, some of the Indian students can become the beneficiaries of the scholarships based on Indian government programs or since the non-governmental funds. The apparentness and availability of these financial support options can have an impact on the perceived appeal of the Czech Republic. It has been established in previous studies that financial aid is a major destination determinant, especially amongst middle- and low-income-students. [13].   
All part-time work opportunities in the time of academic study are another cost factor of the would-be international students. The ability to work on a part-time basis can help to reduce living expenses, collect work experience as a professional, and develop transferable skills [19]. In the Czech Republic, foreign scholars have the right to work part-time if they are studying; this depends on the statutory restrictions about the amount of time that they are allowed to work per week and the type of work. The concentration of part-time jobs, current wage levels, and the availability of local labor market all informed students with respect to the financial choices. To Indian students, a viable opportunity to earn income at the same time increases the cost efficiency of a selected destination [20].  
The employment opportunities after graduation and the corresponding payback is another more distant, yet not less important, financial aspect. Families and students determine the worth of the capital invested in international education in terms of corresponding career paths and income. Destinations that allow them easy career access, either in the host country or internationally speaking, and which provide graduates with high rates of remuneration are inherently more appealing in a financial context. Membership in European Union provides the Czech Republic with a lifetime prospect of having graduates enter the wider European labour market; however, the language barriers and work permit legislation can act against non-EU citizens. [30]The findings of empirical research on the reasons and then limits of Indian students to study in foreign countries proves that the expectant career advantages and estimated returns on investment are crucial factors defining destinations [19] [30].  
The final worth of any educational undertaking depends on the connexon between cost and perceived quality, and it provides the general value proposition. Stakeholders conduct implicit or explicit cost benefit analyses on a regular basis, weighed by the cumulative monetary expenditures against projected academic, professional, and personal rewards [16]. The competitive edge that the Czech Republic has is that it provides a good value proposition, namely European education, which has gained the respect of the whole world, but at a fraction of the price that the usual destinations command. This niche is especially strong in the middle-class Indian families that are trying to afford their children international education and face serious financial limitations that make more expensive options unsustainable [15].  
Empirical research always emphasizes the critical importance of financial aspects in destination choice of higher education. According to a Structural Equation Modelling analysis using global student mobility initiatives in Indian institutions of higher learning, fiscal variables, that is, cost and accessibility of financial aid, played a key role in determining mobility decisions among students [16]. In conducting focused studies on the desires of Indian students towards studying abroad, the tuition fees and cost of living were found to be among the greatest factors, often second only to academic standards [7], [13]. Comparative studies of Indian student mobility to the European countries also revealed that cost-effectiveness was the factor that formed the main force behind the increasing trend towards European destinations as the alternative to the more costly Anglophone countries [9], [11].  
The financial aspect is something that cannot be detached to a wider range of influences. As an example, the cost-effectiveness of a host nation can serve as a means of access to students with a wide range of socio-economic backgrounds and this in turn can bring more diversity and inclusion to the academic world [5]. Furthermore, financial stress may negatively influence academic achievement, personal health, and general satisfaction, making affordability a decisive variable, which goes beyond accessibility to academic performance and experiences quality [28].  
The Czech Republic is noteworthy for its financial benefits, which are crucial in the marketing and recruitment of the country. Clearing information about tuition fees, cost of living, availability of scholarships, and part-time working environments can enable the potential Indian students and their families to make informed choices. Offering detailed financial planning software, cost-calculation applications, and the testimonies of already existing Indian students who successfully manage the financial management in the Czech Republic can only enhance the destination appeal even more. Therefore, the creation of scholarship programmes that are directly focused on Indian students would likely cement the competitive position of the Czech Republic and would draw extremely successful scholars who may seek more expensive options [10].   
3.2.3. Cultural and Social Factors   
The cultural milieu, social integration processes, language dynamics, perceptions of safety, patterns of lifestyle and the presence of support networks in the host country are cultural and social variables. Such variables play a significant role in the choice of the destination as well as future experiences, level of satisfaction, and academic performance of students at the destination. To international researchers, moving to a new country will require the need to negotiate new cultural standards, form new social relationships and adapt to different lifestyle norms, which are both enriching and at the same time, a source of difficulty.[5]  
The extent of cultural similarity or dissimilarity between the two home and host countries acts as a multiplexed determinant. Cultural congruence may be used to enhance the adaptation and reduce the culture shock thereby making culturally similar destinations more desirable [6]. On the other hand, the cultural difference can appeal to students who want to experience something new, self-grow, and internally master the practice of cross-cultural competence. The Czech Republic is a very different place in the circumstances of Indian scholars, where European customs, value systems, and social conventions are strongly prominently different when compared to India. The cultural difference thus created can be a challenge as well as an incentive based on the motivation and ability to adjust to it [30].  
The study of the experience of international students proves that cultural adjustment is a significant issue that affects performance and academic success, as well as psychological wellbeing and general satisfaction. [6] Formal research studies on intercultural transitions in postsecondary education have focused on both the processes of adjustment and adapting to cultural differences, establishing that students who successfully go through the transition and develop intercultural competence experience fewer negative experiences more often [6]. Using the example of Indian students studying in the Czech Republic, the facilitative factors can include organized orientation programmes, specific intercultural training, and cultural exchange experience, which would lead to the increased attractiveness of the country and to the academic success of students.[6]  
Language is one of the defining cultural and functional determinants. Even though the Czech higher education sector has a significant number of English-taught programmes, the Czech language continues to dominate in terms of the everyday communication. The low level of English speaking among the local population beyond the big cities is also an obstacle among the international students as it influences their performance concerning daily task execution, utilization of services, interaction with locals and complete assimilation of the Czech society. On the other hand, linguistic diversity can be considered as a valuable resource by students that view language acquisition as a chance to improve personally(1), [30]. There have been empirical studies that have found that language barrier is a usual challenge when it comes to Indian students in European destinations, but students tend to adapt to this issue over time and can even consider language acquisition a beneficial skill.  
One of the most important issues for international students and their family members is safety and security. Conceptions about security include physical security which includes low rates of crime and lack of violent and aggressive acts, political stability and guard against discrimination or harassment. The Czech Republic is generally considered as a safe country with the low level of crime and the stable political situation in the country, thus presenting a great attraction to the potential newcomers. To the Indian parents making decisions about their children in terms of overseas studies, the question of safety often comes into the limelight as a major concern. Cases of hostility, bigotry, or intimidation against international students in some nations have contributed to safety concern and changing the choice of destinations. The results have shown that the opinions of safety have a significant impact on the destination choice, which pushes students and families to actively search the information about the crime rates, political situation, and the attitude toward foreign students [18].  
The presence of an Indian diaspora or a student body in a host nation is a relevant social variable. The existing groups of Indians also provide social support, cultural understanding, exchange of information, and networking opportunities to newcomers. These communities may help in easy transitions, reduce sense of isolation, and offer practical support in relation to accommodation, orientation and cultural adjustment. The large population of Indian students that is increasingly taking shape in the Czech Republic, especially in the metropolis cities like Prague and Brno, acts as a desirable pull factor to the other successful students. Social network and student mobility studies have proved that co-national communities play a very important role in destination choice and facilitating the accommodation process. (2)   
Students need to feel related and belong to the surrounding community, which social integration and the friendliness of the local population can bring (in SDT terms). The places that are considered as cordial and receptive to international students are more desirable. It is important for students to have a chance to connect with local ones, make cross-cultural friends and be accepted in their host countries. Studies have been done on the satisfaction of international students, and it is always observed that social integration is a major factor of overall satisfaction and well-being [23]. In the case of the Czech Republic, making campus life more inclusive, facilitating intercultural interaction, and turning to local students to encourage their interaction with international ones will help the country improve socialization and the general experience of the students.   
The quality of life has different elements such as climate, urban setting, recreational facilities, healthcare, transport, and the general way of life. Czech Republic has the high quality of life and the well-developed infrastructure, public transportation, available healthcare, and cultural and recreational opportunities. Prague is especially the city of historical beauty, of colorful culture, of cosmopolitan ambiance. In the case of students, the factors of quality-of-life lead to overall satisfaction and wellbeing, and, thus, destinations with high quality of life are more appealing. Student mobility studies have revealed that lifestyle issues are important during destination selection and satisfaction although in some cases secondary to academic and monetary factors [29].   
Other social and cultural factors that are relevant are geographic location and travel opportunities. The central European location of Czech Republic allows easy access to other European states thus students can travel, learn about other people and join pan-European networks [18] . To the Indian students, the possibility of visiting several European countries during study is a bonus that becomes value-adding to the learning process. It is a pull factor, as this geographic advantage is more European destinations compared to the geographically more isolated alternatives [20].   
The status of studying in Europe, cultural capital, may also affect destination choice. To several Indian students and parents, studying in Europe undertakings come with social status and cultural capital that helps in boosting the profile of the student and family prestige. The fact that it is related to European culture, history, and intellectual traditions can be attractive, despite the fact that the country (the Czech Republic) in question may not be as recognizable as more ancient places of sightseeing [20]. This is the symbolic aspect of destination choice that is hard to measure yet it does play an important role in determining tastes and decisions.  
 The empirical research has given much importance to the factors of culture and social influence in determining the mobility of international students. An examination of the reasons and limitations of Indian students moving to foreign countries has also shown that the cultural variables including the quest to achieve cultural exposure and the cultural issues that concern cultural adaptation played a major role in determining the destination choice [19]. A study of the experiences of international students in Latvia, a Central European destination with some similarities to the Czech Republic, has identified cultural factors and the overall appeal of the region as the major driving force behind the 
Indian students [30]. Another research article on student Kerala to European migration also 
highlighted the significance of socio-economic status and cultural assimilation in defining the experiences and satisfaction rate of students [2].   
The interaction between the cultural determinants and the Self-Determination Theory (SDT) seems to be extremely salient. The settings, which encourage autonomy, create access to competence development, and support relatedness, will probably become more desirable and supportive to positive learning results [34]. To Indian students who have to manage the contradictions between traditional values emphasizing the interdependence of the family and the values of the West that are often associated with individualism, Czech environment, with its blend of European and Central-European traditions, could offer a unique place of identity formation and personal growth [35].    
In the Czech Republic, the multifaceted approach is required to deal with cultural and social determinants. The acculturation and integration can be facilitated by augmenting support mechanisms that include orientation programmes, language training, cultural integration programmes and psychosocial counselling of international scholars [5]. The possibility of facilitating intercultural interactions will help bridge the cultural differences and build the platforms where students of Indian and Czech heritage will be able to exchange their insights [6]. To attract and retain international talent the campus and the areas near the campus should be inclusive, non-discriminatory, and conducive. In addition, its attractiveness due to the cultural richness, safety, quality of life, and the presence of a supportive Indian student community can be enhanced through effective communication of such factors, which will increase the prospects of attracting new enrolments to the country [30].   
3.2.4. Psychological Factors   
Continuing the Self-Determination Theory (SDT) model described above, psychological motivations are one of the critical determinants of destination preferences of international students. Instead of restating the theoretical basis, the current section analyses how the notions of autonomy, competence, and relatedness are operationalized when it comes to Indian students who chose the Czech Republic as the study destination.   
Autonomy is also displayed through the desires of students to become independent and have agency over their lives and be free of home-country academic or social restrictions. To many Indian academics, international education presents the opportunity of self-authorizing learning options and pursuing independent existence. The European academic system of the Czech Republic, combined with a student-focused pedagogical atmosphere, is sure to appeal to people who want to have more control in their academic and personal career.   
Competence is linked with the judgments of academic quality, skill training and employability among the students. The decisions to study in the Czech Republic can be influenced by the anticipations of high education, education accredited internationally, and opportunities to expand professional skills. The perceived academic rigor and accessibility of research infrastructure directly predetermine perceived competence and preparedness of students to work on global labor markets.   
Relatedness entails the internal desire of belonging and substantive social relations. The presence of a recognized group of Indian students, attitudes towards security, and integrative institutional environments can have a significant impact on choice of destination. Students will be more likely to report high levels of satisfaction and psychological adaptation when they expect to be integrated into society and accepted by the culture.   
Besides, long-term outcomes are influenced by the quality of motivation an autonomous or extrinsically regulated motivation. Students whose choice is aligned with internal objectives and personal goals tend to have a greater level of satisfaction and well-being than those whose choices are aimed at the external factors and which are caused by family influence or status issues.   
In the framework of the mobility of Indian students to the Czech Republic, SDT provides a useful analytical tool that can be used to explain the relationship of the psychological needs and structural pull factors. As a result, the attractiveness of Czech Republic cannot be associated with only economic or academic advantages, but also with the ability to promote the autonomy of students, their competence development, and social adaptation. 
3.3. Indian Students in International Higher Education   
India has become one of the most important source countries of international students in the world with hundreds of thousands of Indian nationals enrolling into institutions of higher learning in other countries every year [33]. This section provides a critical assessment of the trends and the pattern of Indian student mobility, the motivation factors driving Indian students into foreign education and the obstacles they face in the foreign academic set ups [2]. The subtle understanding of the contextual peculiarities of the Indian student mobility is what is required to divide the factors that predetermine both the reasons and the methods by which the Indian students choose the very specific destinations, and the Czech Republic is not an exception [20].   
3.3.1. Trends and Patterns of Indian Student Mobility   
The movement of Indian students has been growing at an unprecedented pace during the past twenty years and has become the result of a combination of demographic, economic and educational factors [2]. India has the highest number of youth population in the world with millions of learners finishing their secondary schooling every year seeking tertiary education opportunities [33]. However, the Indian ability of the higher education system, though large in absolute sense, is not sufficient to satisfy this vast demand of high-quality education. It is this incessant lack of supply and demand coupled with rising ambitions and increasing accessibility of education by the growing middle classes of India, which has led to the motivating wave of students to foreign universities [19].    
Empirical data based on the ICEF Monitor and various national repositories show that the count of 
Indian students in foreign countries has increased since the beginning of the 2000s by approximately 200,000 up to the present days with over 750,000 students being the second top source of international students in the world, only after China. [33]Although the COVID-19 pandemic had caused a momentary halt in such flows of movement, the restoration of normalcy has been strong, and it is expected to keep growing in the coming annum.    
The Indian students have traditionally shown high tendencies towards the Anglophone destinations, and this includes the United States, the United Kingdom, Canada, and Australia. These countries have been receiving most of the Indian international scholars, because of the status of their universities, the dominance of the English medium of instruction, the strong networks of the Indian diaspora, as well as the feeling of better career opportunities [20]. The US is the most predominant destination as it accepts large populations of Indian students especially in the STEM fields at graduate level. The United Kingdom is also a large hub particularly of the master programmes. In Canada and Australia, the growth of Indian enrolments has been faster in the recent past due to permissive immigration policies and procurement of permanent residency.   
Nonetheless, the last years have been characterized by a significant diversification of preferences in destination among Indian students. There are several factors which are intertwined that have brought about this shift. First, the rising of the cost and to a greater extent tightening of immigration policies at the old destinations especially the United States and the United Kingdom have made students to consider other mobility opportunities [33]. Secondly, the increased knowledge about learning opportunities in non-traditional destinations, through digital information sources and professionalism of the educational consultant, has widened the scope of admissible options by prospective students [2]. Third, the internationalization policies embraced by universities in other countries such as active recruitment campaigns towards India have increased the visibility and appeal of the alternative destinations [7]. Fourth, geopolitical factors, including fear of safety and discrimination and unpredictability of visa policies in some traditional destinations, have also influenced the preferences of students and moderated them.  
This diversification has been a blessing to European countries. Germany, France, the  
Netherlands, and even Central European and Eastern European nations such as Czech Republic,  Poland, Hungary, etc., have been receiving more Indian students. A study conducted by Mukherjee and others focused on the movement of Indian students to European countries of choice namely Germany and France and reported the drivers behind this trend [9], [11]. This paper established that these countries were becoming more and more appealing to Indian students due to the combination of good education, cheaper rates than the Anglophone destinations, and opportunities within the European Union.   
The Czech Republic is an emerging destination. Although it is still not drawing Indian student numbers equivalent to Germany or UK, in the last 10 years, the number of Indian students enrolling in Czech universities has been steadily increasing [2]. This has been most evident in certain areas like medicine whereby the Czech medical schools have aggressively taken in Indian students, and in engineering and business courses. The existence of an existing community of Indian students in such cities as Prague and Brno has resulted in creating the network effects that lead to the further growth [38].  
The trends of Indian student migration depend on the sphere of study, the level of study and socioeconomic status. Indian students studying in foreign countries at the undergraduate level are often concentrated in the engineering, Computer science and Business programmes. Graduate level mobility in contrast is more heterogeneous in its distribution of disciplines with an intense representation in STEM, business administration, the social sciences, and humanities.[2] Medicine is a unique scenario where a good percentage of Indian students are studying medical degrees abroad and particularly in countries where the admission standards are relatively lower and the cost of tuition is lower compared to India. Indicatively, the Czech Republic has been identified to be a specifically successful place to recruit Indian medical students [10].  
Academic level patterns show that the greatest percentage of Indian international students is enrolled in master programmes, bachelor’s and then doctoral programmes. One-year master programmes that are common in the United Kingdom have become especially popular. On the other hand, the Czech master programmes (normally two years long) are aligned with the European standards and allow students a longer educational period [7].  
In a socio-economic dimension, most of the Indian international students belong to middle and uppermiddle-income families that have the financial resources to finance foreign education. However, recent developments are characterized by a growing amount of heterogeneity, as students in smaller urban centers and low-income families also study abroad, often through scholarship programmes or by choosing less expensive destinations. Empirical studies on migration of middle-class Indian students have highlighted the contribution of aspirations, family strategies and agents of intermediary recruitment in shaping the mobility pattern. [14].   
The trends in the gender structure of Indian student mobility have been changing over the last several decades, as there is a clearly observable key change in the ratio of female subjects getting involved in studying abroad; however, most of the representatives remain male. Traditionally, the culture setting, the parental fears related to the safety, and the established gender role patterns have restricted the freedom of movement of a woman [20]. The fact that these barriers are gradually on the decline can be seen through evolving social perceptions, and the recorded success of female scholars in other countries to show the real potential of such ventures and their viability and feasibility in a logistically sound manner [29].  
There is also geospatial difference that has an impressive effect on India. The states with high levels of economic development, higher educational levels, and increased exposure to international opportunities are the most significant contributors of students in foreign academic programmes. Maharashtra, Delhi, Karnataka, Tamil Nadu, Telangana and Kerala become crucial source states. The empirical research concerning the migration of the Kerala students to Europe has traced the select dynamics that pertain to this regional flux, including the contribution of the dissatisfaction with the quality of education in the home country, and the facilitation of the process that is provided by the already existing migration networks. [2].   
The impact of the intermediaries, especially the educational consultants and recruitment agents, has a significant effect on the trend of Indian student mobility. A large number of the Indian students rely on these consultants to guide them on the complex procedures of university selection, application preparation, visa application, and logistics. These intermediaries hold significant influence on destination preferences thus guiding the student flows on the destinations to particular countries or institutions due to their affiliations and commissioning structures, as well as area of specialisation. Studies have also established significant differences in quality of consultancy services and moral principles of services offered by educational consultancies, which means that some companies may offer worthwhile consultancy, whereas others perform activities leading to misguidance. [12].   
Such trends and patterns would be critical in putting into perspective the decisions of Indian students in relation to the Czech Republic. The Czech Republic is placed as an alternative to the traditional Anglophone alternatives and other European alternatives, which can provide a unique blend of quality, cost, location in Europe and particular programme advantages. Its growth as an Indian student destination indicates broader general diversification and value-seeking in overseas education[12].   
3.3.2 Motivations and Challenges Faced by Indian Students Abroad   
Push factors in India and pull factors in the countries of immigration, as well as personal preferences and family planning strategies, are all part of the intricate and multifaceted incentives that lead Indian students studying abroad to pursue higher education [19]. An excellent grasp of these motivation forces will provide knowledge of the expectations held by the Indian students in regard to international education and the way that the destinations like Czech Republic can meet the requirements [4].   
	I. 	Academic and Educational Motivations   
The main reason why the Indian students opt to study overseas is the search of better standard of learning that is perceived to be better or unique compared to education offered in India. Even though higher education in India is a large system, there are concerns about the quality of academic work, outdated curriculums, lack of infrastructure and limited research prospects in many institutions and this is driving students to overseas options. The causes of Indian international students not joining master programmes in their native country were examined in an empirical study by Chanda et al. and the analysis revealed that perceived loss in quality, limited specialization, and the research facilities were critical inhibitory factors [15]. The desire to learn under outstanding talents, use state of the art facilities, engage in innovative research and an education both relevant around the globe and compliant to international standards drive such scholars.    
This is an extra push because specialized academic programmes concentrations are either not offered or not well-developed in India. As an example, those students who want niche engineering major, interdisciplinary programmes, or medical specialization might find greater opportunities in the foreign market [4]. In addition, the presence of English-taught courses in non-English speaking countries, as is the case in the Czech Republic, eliminates a language barrier and also allows access to various educational philosophies and points of view at the same time.  
	II. 	Career and Economic Motivations   
Professional growth and improved job opportunities are major reasons that make a good percentage of Indian students pursue education in foreign countries. The international degree, especially a degree of a well reputed institution, is seen to enhance the employability of the individual, the availability of better job opportunities and a better pay not only in India but also in other parts of the world. Indeed, empirical research findings clearly show a career consideration as one of the most important motivators among Indian international students [7], [13],[19].  Many students argue that studying in another country provides them with valuable skillsets, valid credentials and broadening their networks, giving them advantages in finding jobs after graduation. The ability to gain international work experience by means of work placements during their study or through work after graduation is a very strong motivating factor for students to study in another country. In addition, studying outside of India gives students an opportunity to either support their desire to obtain international employment, or to build international professional experience, which will ultimately return to India with additional credentials and valuable exposure. Students who go to countries which provide poststudy work visas and a route to permanent residency through their work experience are especially interested in studying abroad for these reasons. There is an economic rationale behind the investment in education overseas with respect to increasing lifetime wages after graduation; as such, many families view investing in their child's education as a way to obtain a large return on their investment through better employment opportunities and higher earnings. This financial incentive often has a tremendous impact on middle-class families that are sacrificing a significant amount of money to pay for their student's education outside of India.  
III. 	Personal and Developmental Motivations   
Beyond the standard education and career objectives, there is a significant percentage of Indian students who are motivated by the idea of self-advancement. Many students imagine studying abroad as a way to achieve personal growth, increasing their independence, maturing and self-discovery. To young adults who are in the transitional stage to adulthood, living independently in a foreign country, facing new challenges and being in charge of their own lives is a critical encounter with development. Empirical studies supported by the Self-Determination Theory have reported that motives related to autonomy and self-development are important factors that define the choice to study overseas. [4], [29].   
Cultural exposure and desire to experience different cultures and their ways of living and thinking are some of the influencing factors driving many students. The likelihood of travelling, learning about other different societies, developing intercultural competence, and broadening world view is not only treasured but also in terms of a professional benefit in a highly globalized environment [4].  To some students, adventure and excitement of living in a foreign country is a motivating factor.  
	IV. 	Social and Family Motivations   
There is also a factor of familial expectations and the social culture pressure, which motivates the Indian students to attend overseas education. In most Indian families, especially the families of the middle and upper-middle social groups, foreign education is very valued and interpreted as the measure of personal achievement and status. Parents often have significant expectations of their children to study abroad and can have a strong level of control in the decision-making process. Empirical studies have reported that even though there are learners making independent decisions on studying abroad, others are coerced into a strong form of family influence that could undermine the quality of their motivation and influence future academic and sociocultural engagements. (2), [19].   
There is a significant impact of peer and social network dynamics. When the familiar, family members or local people take up study abroad and they see positive reports, these experiences create aspirational intentions and provide operational intelligence that facilitates the processes of decision making that are ancillary. With the introduction of social media and online communication platforms, these network-mediated phenomena have become even more acute such that data relating to overseas academic activities becomes more accessible and visible [19].   
	V. 	Challenges Faced by Indian Students Abroad   
As much as there are many opportunities in studying abroad, Indian students face a lot of challenges which affect their experiences and their results. The need to understand these challenges is essential in ensuring that the host destinations including Czech Republic can develop effective support mechanisms [6].  
VI. 	Academic Challenges 
The students of India might face academic problems regarding the dissimilarity between the educational systems, pedagogical methods, and institutional requirements of the Indian context. The transition to a Western-style of education based on discussion and critical thinking as opposed to an examination-driven and content-based curriculum is usually a major challenge. Although the programmes are carried out in English, it is possible that the language barriers hinder the understanding and participation. Empirical research has revealed that academic adjustment is a common problem amongst foreign students and requires premeditated time and institutional coverage. [6].   
VII. 	Financial Challenges 
Although a high level of planning is done, a good percentage of Indian students have been subjected to financial pressure during their studies in foreign countries. The cost of international education, even in relatively low-cost countries of residence, is a significant cost. Unpredictability in the exchange rates, unplanned spending, and limited financial capabilities may cause stress, thus affecting the wellness and academic performance of students [15]. Also, time constraints associated with the need to work part-time to make ends meet have a negative impact on academic activity [28].  
VIII. 	Cultural and Social Challenges:  
Among the most faced challenges faced by the Indian students studying in foreign countries, cultural adaptation and social integration have been reported. These people have to overcome some unknown cultural norms, social behaviors and ways of communicating and this results in culture shock, homesickness and sensation of being isolated especially at the first months of their overseas placement. The process of creating new social networks and developing significant relationships within an international setting may be laborious, particularly in the cases when language barriers are present, or domestic students have the tendency to avoid interacting with international students. Empirical studies of intercultural transition have placed on record, the numerous aspects of cultural adjustment, the aspects that favour effective adaptation, and those that hamper effective adjustment.[6] [30].   
IX. 	Discrimination and Safety Concerns 
Some of the Indian students might face discrimination, racism, or harassment in their new places of residence and this can significantly affect their wellbeing and belonging. The cases of violence or discrimination of international students as witnessed in different countries create safety fears that could discourage potential students. Empirical data shows that satisfaction and perceptions of safety and discrimination are essential factors that determine the satisfaction of international students in choosing a destination. [18], [30].   
	X. 	Psychological and Mental Health Challenges 
The combination of academic pressures, economic complexity, problems with adapting to the culture, and social isolation significantly influence the mental wellbeing of international students. This population is subject to anxiety, depressive symptoms and chronic stress.[23] [6] Often mental-health services and culturally informed counseling are not accessible, which only increases such issues. Modern studies are becoming increasingly convinced that the psychological health of international learners should be taken care of to achieve academic success and general satisfaction.  [28].   
XI. 	Visa and Immigration Challenges 
The visa processes, adherence to immigration policies, and victimization of uncertainties about employment opportunities available after graduation or the host country status are the factors that create psychological stress and erode the perceived security and long-term planning among the students (2). Alterations on immigration policy, particularly restrictive ones, can cause apprehension and reduce the appeal of a destination [20].   
XII. 	Family Separation and Responsibilities 
The distance between the family members, especially in time of significant family occasions or a crisis, is an emotionally difficult process to many Indian students. Besides, a percentage of students who face demands to support relatives or relatives are expected to support them financially, which will lead to the emergence of conflicts between personal career ambitions or the urge to obtain international experience and family demands.    
These problems have been recorded through research studies specifically aimed at the experiences of Indian students in other countries. Research on the reasons and limitations of Indian students moving to foreign countries revealed that although the students were driven by the prospects of education and employment, they also faced a lot of challenges related to cultural adjustment, money, and separation with their families [19]. A study done on Indian students in most European destinations has enlightened on not only the opportunities that such students have but also on the challenges they face, hence the need to have supportive systems and inclusive environments. [2], [30].   
In the case of Czech Republic, the understanding of these motivations and challenges is a condition to the development of effective recruitment strategies and supportive services. The marketing efforts should highlight how the institutions of higher education in the Czech Republic can address the academic, professional, and personal growth goals of the Indian students, and at the same time alleviate the cost, safety, and institutional support concerns.[10] Moreover, the support services should be designed to enable a smooth process of academic acculturation, cultural assimilation, social integration and psychological well-being hence recognizing the unique needs and challenges faced by the Indian students [5].   
3.4 Czech Republic as a Study Destination   
Over the past two decades, the Czech Republic has become a very appealing destination by international students including the Indian ones [39]. This section focuses on an introduction to the system of Czech higher-education and considers the specific features that make Czech Republic attractive to international scholars and specifically examines other factors that impact destination decisions among Indian students [20].  
3.4.1 Overview of Czech Higher Education System   
The Czech higher education system has a rich and long history, some of the universities can be tracked to the mediaeval times. Charles University formed in 1348 is one of the oldest and flagship universities in Europe. Modern Czech higher education system was adjusted after the Velvet Revolution of 1989 and the following democratization and adoption of a market economy in the country. Later reforms in the 2000s occurred to harmonies the system with European standards via the Bologna Process which introduced a three-cycle system of degrees (bachelor, master, doctoral) and encouraged movement and recognition throughout European systems of higher learning [40].  
The system of higher education in the Czech Republic consists of state universities, private universities and public universities. Most of the institutions are public universities that are mostly state-supported and include the most prestigious universities [41]. The programmes that are provided in these universities cover a great spectrum of subjects, such as humanities, social sciences, natural sciences, engineering, medicine, and arts. Private universities that have grown in number since 1990s are more likely to specialize in each subject including business, law, and social sciences. State universities are also specialized universities which are dedicated to subjects like military and police education [41].  
Traditionally, tuition-free studies in the Czech language are offered in Czech universities to international students by the Czech state. The programmes offered in foreign languages, which are mainly English programmes are however normally charged. This two-tier system enables foreign students willing and able to pursue their studies in Czech to enjoy free education, and those who prefer programmes in English pay fees which although substantial, tend to be lower as compared to the fees in Western European states or other Anglophone destinations [41].  
Bologna Process has helped Czech higher education to become internationalized. Czech universities have proliferated English programmes especially at the master and doctoral degrees to allow the entry of international students and increase their global image. European Credit Transfer and Accumulation System (ECTS) facilitate recognition of credit and free flow of students in institutions in Europe. The universities in Czech embrace the European exchange programmes like Erasmus+ that attract students studying in other European nations on temporary basis [41], [42].  
The quality assurance of higher education in the Czech Republic is conducted by the National Accreditation Bureau that conducts systematic examination and accreditation of study programmes and institutions. Though the Czech universities are not strategically placed in the world ranking that is normally dominated by Anglophone institutions, some of them have strong reputations, especially in certain fields of discipline. In particular, the best examples include Charles University, Czech Technical University in Prague, Masaryk University in Brno, and Palacky University in Olomouc that can attract a significant number of international students [41], [42].   
The Czech higher education system has very strong focus on research, particularly at the doctoral stage and Czech universities are members of European research networks and funding opportunities. This research orientation gives the graduate students the chance to participate in research projects, financial aid, and even cooperate with the scholars of the international community [41], [42].   
3.4.2 Attractiveness for International Students   
The attractiveness of the Czech Republic is a destination country to international higher education students, especially the ones with an Indian background, can be explained by a shooting-star of academic, financial, geographic, cultural, and pragmatic aspects. The interpretation of these traits provides explanatory information about the choice of the Indian scholars and help to explain the competitive positioning of the Czech Republic in comparison with other available locations [7].  
	I. 	Academic Quality and Program Availability   
The institutions of higher education in Czech offer quality education in a wide range of fields with specific strong sides in such areas as medicine, engineering, natural sciences and arts.  Czech academic sphere is credited and prestigious by the long-standing academic tradition of such institutions like Charles University.  To the student nationals of India, the availability of the English-taught programmes consistent with their interests makes a determinant factor in their institutional selection.  The number of courses available in English taught in Czech universities has also increased and especially medicine, engineering, business, and computer science, which have gained much popularity among Indian students [43].  One of the weaknesses and the main draw is medical education. The Czech Republic offers six-year programmes of the Doctor of medicine which are taught in English and are recognized internationally, such as the accreditation of medical councils in India, in the United States and other jurisdictions.  A combination of high-quality medical education and relatively low tuition fees compared to medical schools in the Western countries or even to the Indian and other privately run medical colleges in India has made the Czech Republic a favorite destination among potential physicians of India and other countries. A study conducted on student migration of Kerala to Europe has particularly mentioned the Czech Republic as a medical study destination. [2].   
	II. 	Financial Affordability   
Indian students are extremely cost-conscious, as it is mentioned in in Section 3.2.2 the Czech  
Republic offers significant cost-efficiencies. The cost of tuition at English-taught courses at Czech state universities traditionally lies between the price of two thousand and fifteen thousand a year, depending on the programme and the level. This is a significant decrease compared to tuition fees in the United Kingdom (around £15.000-£30.000), the United States (about $20.000-$50.000) and some states in Western Europe. Regarding life costs, the Czech Republic, particularly the areas outside Prague city, remain relatively low in terms of cost of living as compared to the rest of Western Europe. Students can afford cheap housing, and the daily spending to food, transportation, and recreation are affordable. The low cost of Czech Republic makes it affordable to middle-income Indian families who would want to provide their children with European education but cannot afford more expensive countries. The fact that European education, which has international awareness, could be acquired at a fraction of the price of the traditional destinations is a very salient repelling force [15].  III. 	Geographic Location and European Access   
The geographic location of the Czech Republic is central Europe, which is a strategic opportunity. The state lies centrally on the European continent, thereby granting easy access to other European countries hence giving the students the opportunity to travel, experience different cultures with others, and create pan-European networks. The fact that a student of Indian origin will have the prospect of visiting several European countries during their academic programme will add significant weight to the learning process and will make this an attractive offer.[44]  
Being a country of the European Union and Schengen Area, Czech Republic grants students the access to the larger European area. Non-EU students do not face unrestrained opportunities; however, they usually have the right to move freely within the Schengen Zone throughout their study, which simplifies the integration into the local culture and the establishment of professional contacts. Besides, the EU membership will mean that the degrees earned in the Czech Republic will be recognized throughout the EU, which can make those degrees more emblazoned or allow to study in other European jurisdictions [44].  
IV. 	Safety and Quality of Life   
Czech Republic is an area that is safely considered to be a safe country with low crime rates, stable political situation and a high standard of living. In the case of Indian parents and students who value the aspect of safety, especially in the backdrop of the reported cases of violence or discrimination of international students in other countries, the image of the country being a safe place serves as a powerful pull factor. It ranks well in a number of quality-of-life indicators, with strong healthcare, good transport infrastructure, clean environment and strong culture [41], [44].  
The capital of Prague is acclaimed to have an ancient aesthetic, dynamic culture and a cosmopolitan atmosphere. It is always in the list of the most beautiful cities in Europe and offers a high standard of life with the combination of antique and contemporary facilities. The other Czech neighborhoods like Brno, Olomouc and Plzen also have favorable living conditions with cheaper prices and warmer communal environment [30].  
	V. 	Cultural Richness and European Experience   
Czech Republic is a country that boasts of a rich cultural heritage, including historical architecture, museums, theatres, music, and the fine arts. To the students who are fascinated with European culture and history, this country offers a detachable academic experience. The cultural specificity of Western and Eastern Europe due to its location as the center of the intersection of these cultures gives it a certain cultural trait that synthesizes the elements of various European cultures.    
The opportunity to explore the unique European lifestyle, which is contrasted with social and cultural backgrounds of the countries of India and Anglophone countries, can be interesting to the students who seek personal development and intercultural competence. [21]Even though the cultural difference might be a challenge, it also presents learning and development opportunities.  
VI. 	Presence of Indian Student Community   
The growing population of Indian students studying in Czech universities particularly in metro cities like Prague and Brno creates network effects that bring about further growth of the population group. The established communities of Indian students provide the essential social support and exchange of information, as well as a familiarity of the culture to the new students. The work of Indian student associations, holding cultural events and working of informal networks all facilitate the adjustment process and alleviate the sense of isolation. Empirical studies have always shown that the existence of co-national communities is a major factor that determines the destination selection and the successful accommodation. , [30].   
VII. 	Language and Communication   
Although the official language is the Czech one, which is used in the daily life, the presence of programmes offered in English can eradicate the major barrier to academic activity the language barrier. Another interesting group of younger Czech nationals, particularly in urban areas and in university settings, is skilled in English thus making intercommunicating easy. However, a limited proficiency of English by the larger population and select service environments can be a hindrance to the everyday life of the people. To those students prone to learning Czech, the language teaching is generally available, and the command of the language can enhance socialization and provide additional opportunities [41],[43], [44].  
VIII. 	Immigration and Work Opportunities   
The immigration policies of the Czech Republic towards international students are rather liberal; however, they are not as liberal as the immigration policies of some other European countries. The applicants have a right to obtain long-term residence permits for the entire course of their studies and are usually allowed to work part-time (limited to 20 hours per week during the study years and unlimited during vacation times). The provisions can provide students with an opportunity to accumulate professional experience and, at the same time, alleviate their financial situation [45].  
Comparatively, the range of post-graduation job opportunities, in contrast to such jurisdictions as Canada or Australia, which offer explicit post-study work visas, is relatively limited. However, the alumni that find employment in the Czech Republic can apply to labor permits or employee cards. The local labor force qualifies the demand of skilled human resource in a variety of major sectors, particularly in information technology and engineering among other important sectors such as health care and thus offers a variety of opportunities to the new graduates. Moreover, EU Blue Card regime promotes the attraction of highly skilled non-EU professionals throughout the entire European Union, a tool, that can also benefit Czech graduates who want to work outside of the country [45].   
IX. 	Institutional Support and Services   
Czech universities have increasingly realized the necessity of accommodating international students and have created international offices, orientation programmes and support services. The level and quality of these services vary among institutions, although there is an increased realization of the need to align international students both academically and socially. The types of support include buddy programmes, language courses, cultural activities and counselling services [5].   
3.5 Challenges and Limitations   
On the one hand, there are a great number of attractions in the Czech Republic, but, on the other hand, the country faces challenges in the competition of international students. It has relatively low global visibility and brand awareness compared to the traditional destinations, thus the need to be proactive in its marketing and recruitment efforts. In the daily environment, language barrier will be a major problem to students who are not proficient in the Czech language. Moreover, the climate with cold winters might be new and uncomfortable to the students used to the tropical climate of the Indian territories. Bureaucratic processes, including visa applications and renewing of residence permits, are generally complex and time consuming. Moreover, despite the overall welcoming demeanour of the Czech Republic, there may be occasional cases of discrimination or xenophobia, although they are not so widespread, and thus can affect the experience of students [46].  
The literature on the Czech Republic as a destination country among Indian students is rather scarce, however, the works on Indian students in other Central and Eastern European nations provide relevant information. The analysis of Indian students studying in Latvia proves while language barriers and cultural adjustment are major challenges faced by them, the availability of various types of educational programmes and lower overall costs are key motivating factors for students from India [30]. Research on student migration of Kerala to Europe also included the Czech Republic in the list of examined destinations, which highlights the impact{Citation} of the quality and affordability of education. [2].   
To sum up, the Czech Republic is a unique blend of features that make it an attractive destination the Indian students should travel to find high-quality and affordable tertiary education in Europe.  
Its educational capabilities, especially in medicine and engineering, financial accessibility, central European location, safety and the growing Indian student body make it a credible alternative to both the classic Anglophone destinations and other European alternatives.  However, to increase its competitiveness, the organization will require long-term work to raise its visibility, increase support services, integration, and effective communication of its value proposition to the potential Indian students and their families [46]. 
 
 
 
 
 
  
4. Practical Part (study, research, analysis and developing solutions) 
As discussed previously, the main data of the current research was gathered within a five-week period by use of a structured online survey distributed by Google Forms. A multi-channel strategy was used to recruit a heterogeneous sample of participants, including digital platforms (like WhatsApp and Facebook groups, as well as the official portal, called Study in Czechia), called Studyin.cz). Also, a snowball sampling design was used to expand to the target population. After the data collection stage was complete, 178 valid responses were received. The survey instrument was structured into thematic blocks such as demographics i.e. name, age, gender, year of arrival, and the university of study of the individual. Sections related to motivational drivers and future intentions used a five-point Likert scale, which ranged between Extremely Important (5) and Not Important at All (1), which ensured that the perception of the students and their drivers could be analysed quantitatively. 
4.1 Demographics of the survey 
To achieve the user-friendly experience and avoid privacy issues the collection of personal data like names and email addresses were made optional. Making these areas optional, the survey aimed at raising the rate of participation and developing a feeling of safety among the respondents. 
 
4.1.1 Age Distribution of Respondents 
The analysis of the age distribution of respondents found that most of the respondents were within the age of 26 to 33 with 91 individuals and it forms the largest percentage of students. This was almost followed by the 18 to 25 age group, which comprised 69 respondents, which is a group of young professionals. Only 16 students fell between the age bracket 34 to 40, with a marginal group of 2 respondents at the age bracket of 40 or above.  
