4.1.3 Year of Arrival in Czech Republic 
During the ten-year study of the period between 2015 and 2025, the early years exhibited a very small level of arrival. For example, there were only five (5) arrivals in 2015 (2.8%) and this number remained below two percent (2%) per annum through 2020. However, incremental changes began in 2021 with a steady increase in arrival data. The greatest volume of change had developed in the latter years of the study. For example, in 2023, twenty-five percent (25%)(n=44) of all arrivals were reported for the participants during this ten-year period and this pattern of growth associated with their arrival. In 2024 and 2025, the next two highest numbers of arrivals, 18% (n=32) and 24%(n=42) respectively, established additional support for the continued strength of immigration into the Czech Republic. 
Thus there was also a significant trend suggesting that close to 66% of all respondents arrived during the three (3) most recent years thus validating that the Czech Republic has quickly increased its prominence as a top source of (both) international education and professional opportunities. Similar evidence regarding the growth of immigration into the Czech Republic, especially from India, is found in a publication from the Czech National Agency for International Education (DZS) "International Student Migration In The Czech Republic" (Czech Ministry of The Interior/IOM 2022) and also from the Czech Statistical Office. 
As of 2022, Indian enrolments had increased by 20% since 2020 due to a 92% visa acceptance rate, expanded engineering courses taught in English, and a cost of living approximately 50-70% less than in Western Europe. In 2024, international students will account for 18% of all students at universities; streamlined online admissions and competitive tuition fees establish the Czech Republic as an attractive location for studying abroad.

4.1.4 Institutional Analysis  
Over two-thirds of the respondents reported attending one of the following institutions: Czech University of Life Sciences (CZU), Czech Technical University (CTU), Charles University (CU), Prague University of Economics and Business (VSE) or University of Chemistry and Technology (UCT). In addition to the above-mentioned schools located in Prague, respondents stated they also attend Masaryk University in Brno and Brno University of Technology (Brno-UT).

4.1.5 Level of Degree 
Participant's academic qualifications are predominantly postgraduate and/or undergraduate degrees; master’s degree candidates make up the majority of the sample (57%, n = 101). The second largest group are undergraduate (42%, n = 75) students. A very small representation exists for PhD students (1%, n = 2). This suggests that Indian students primarily migrate to the Czech Republic in order to pursue professional specialization at the master's degree level. As such, master's degree pathways are the most significant for this demographic.

4.1.6 Language of Study 
Regarding language of instruction, the data reveals a high preference on English-taught programs among the surveyed international students. When asked if their study is in English, and vast majority of 175 respondents (98%) confirmed with YES. In contrast, limited group of students, consisting of 3 individuals (2%), indicated that their program was not taught in English. The motivation and factors are analyzed further in the factors. 
4.2 Factors of the study 
The factors are outlined by the active involvement in the survey with its inherent goal and the satisfaction of the psychological needs. To measure these dimensions in the survey, questions to do with educational quality, degree accreditation, safety, and English language programmed were used. For all 1-5 scale questions, the following assigned values were used: Extremely Important = 5, Very Important = 4, Moderately Important = 3, Slightly Important = 2, and Not Important = 1. Below discuss all the factors starting from highly rated (Extremely important) to least important (Not important). 
4.2.1 Analysis of External Motivational Factors 
a)	English Taught Programs: The availability of English-taught study is the most influential factor for the students. 77.5% (n=138) of students categorized this as extremely important, while 16.9% (n=30) rated it as very important. Combined, over 94% of respondents viewed the language as a decisive factor but with a small impact, individuals with only a marginal 0.6% (n=1) considering it not important. 
 
b)	Quality of Education: Academic standards were primary driver, with 64.0% (n=114) of respondents citing quality of education as extremely important and 23.6% (n=42) as very important. Collectively, nearly 88% of participants prioritized the educational quality of Czech institutions. Only 1.1% (n=2) rated it as slightly important, and 0.6% (n=1) viewed it as not important. 
 
c)	Low Tuition Fee: The financial affordability in respect to academic activities has become a big lure. 62.4% (n=111) of the participants identified low tuition fees as extremely important, while 24.7% (n=44) considered them very important. A small segment of the population, 9.0% (n=16), viewed this factor as moderately important and (n=6) viewed this factor as slightly important (3.4) with only one respondent (0.6%) stating it was not important. 
 
d)	Affordable Living Cost: While analyzing affordability, the general cost of living was highly prioritized. 61.2% (n=109) of respondents rated this as extremely important, and 29.2% 
(n=52) as very important. While students responded with moderately important with (n=15) 
8.4% and slightly important 1.1% (n=2). On the other hand, 0 student responded, “Not Important”. This indicates that for over 90% of the students, the economic manageability of the Czech Republic was a decisive factor in their relocation.  
 
Further, when asked if the cost of living is manageable, the largest segment of the students 57.3% (n=102) described the situation as "manageable but rising." This is a sign of measured optimism, with students currently in a position to meet their expenses whilst being mindful of the rising prices. A total of 35.4% (n=63) of survey respondents positively rated the affordability of the Czech Republic. If you consider the percentage of respondents that selected both "affordable" and "manageable but increasing", nearly 96% of participants considered the Czech Republic to be sustainable as a part of the student's budget. Conversely, a very small portion of respondents (3.4%, n=6) said that the cost of living was "too expensive".  
 
e)	Global Recognition of Degree: This perception played an important part of the students' destination selection process. Of the students, 58.4% (n=104) rated global recognition as Extremely Important and 30.3% (n=54) rated it as “Very Important.” Thus, a total of 88.7% of students rated global recognition as Extremely Important or Very Important. A total of only 1.1% (n=2) of students rated global recognition as Slightly Important and only 0.6% (n=1) of students rated global recognition as Not Important.
 
f)	Scholarship Availability: Compared to other factors, this variable was the most evenly distributed amongst all students. For example, 23.0% (n=41) of the students rated it as Extremely Important and 27.0% (n=48) students rated it as Very Important. The largest single group, 29.8% (n=53), selected Moderately Important. Combined, 20.2% of students rated this aspect at a lower level of importance than Moderate, with 11.8% (n=21) of students rating scholarship availability as Slightly Important and 8.4% (n=15) of students rating it as Not Important. 
 
