4.2.2 Analysis of Internal Motivational Factors:  
a)	Safety and Low crime rate: According to respondents, the most important reason for staying in the Czech Republic was safety. Safety and a low crime rate were rated as extremely important by 78.1% (n=139) of participants and very important by 19.1% (n=34). This suggests that almost 97% of students place a high value on the nation's safe environment. Just 1.1% (n=2) thought it was moderately or slightly important, and just 0.6% (n=1) thought it was unimportant.    
 
Further in the survey, question was asked to rate the safety in Czech Republic from 1 (lowest) to 5 (highest) and the students provided a very high average rating of 4.35. Nearly half of the students (49.4%, n=88) gave the nation's safety the highest possible rating of five stars, according to the distribution of responses. An additional 39.9% (n=71) gave the Czech Republic a rating of 4 stars, indicating that roughly 89% of respondents think it is a very safe place. Perceptions of insecurity, on the other hand, were minimal: only 1.7% (n=3) gave the lowest rating of 1, while 9% (n=16) gave a moderate rating of 3 stars. Notably, not a single respondent chose the 2-star rating.  
 
b)	Job Search Visa (Post Study Work Rights): Having a legal framework available for transitioning from student status into the workforce is a major incentive for obtaining residency. Approximately 66.3% (n=118) of participants feel that Post-Study Work Rights are very important; 26.4% (n=47) considered them to be important. Altogether, over 92% of participants strongly agree regarding how supportive the Job Search Visa will be in their future plans. Only a small number (6.2%, n=11) of students view this area as being of little or no importance (slight) as opposed to the majority who rated it highly significant or very significant (i.e., above average). 
 
c)	Ease of Obtaining a Student Visa: 36.5% (n=65) of the respondents rated the ease of obtaining a student visa as very important, while over half (50.6%, n=90) rated it as extremely important. This implies that in order to draw in and keep this group, efficient immigration procedures are essential. Only 9.6% (n=17) thought this was moderately important, and 3.3% perceived it was either slightly or not important.  
d)	Location in Central Europe (Travel Opportunities): While discussing the geographical advantage of the Czech Republic, (39.3%, n=70) of respondents rated the ease of travel that can be achieved due to the country’s central European location as "extremely important," (38.2%, n=68) rated it as "very important." Although still considered to be a very significant factor for (77.5%) of the entire sample, it was rated with slightly less intensity relative to safety and work rights. (20.8%, n=37) of participants reported that they consider the ease of travel that can be achieved due to the country’s central European location "moderately important". 
 
e)	Indian Community Presence: The factors driving migration include primarily economic (income, employment opportunities) and safety reasons, followed by cultural familiarity and social-support systems. 28.7% (n = 51) of the respondents rated the presence of an Indian community as moderately important; a large number of people continue to value this very highly (27% = 48) as extremely important and 22.5% (n = 40) as very important. The highest number of respondents rated the presence of an Indian community as slightly or not important (21.9%), representing the greatest level of indifference across the factors presented in this survey. 
