4.3 Economic Viability and Financial Integration 
The following section of the survey evaluates the economic sides of the student experience, which specifically focuses on income levels, expenditure patterns, and the role of affordability as a primary reason in the migration approach. 
4.3.1 Employment Status  
Regarding the current work status, 86% (n = 153) of the sample confirmed that they were currently employed (in both part-time and full-time jobs). Conversely, 11.8% (n = 21) of the participants were not presently working, and 0.6% of the students responded with an alternative response by indicating that they were looking for a job. 
When asked whether their work is related to their degree, 34.3% (n = 61) of the respondents indicated that their current job is closely related to the field in which they are studying. Contrarily, 36% (n = 64) of the respondents stated that their current job does not relate to the field in which they are studying, while 28.1% (n = 50) indicated a "somewhat" level of connection between their job and the field they are studying. 
 
4.3.2 Working Hours 
The majority of working students, at 29.2% (n = 52), work between 30 and 40 hours a week. The second category of working hours is working between 20 and 30 hours a week, at 27.0% (n = 48). The least number of working students, at 14.6% (n = 26), work more than 40 hours a week. This shows that most of the working students are fully engaged in professional work. The lowest working hours are working between 10 and 20 hours a week at 12.9% (n = 23), while working less than 10 hours a week at 12.4% (n = 22).

4.3.3 Financial Self Sufficiency 
When evaluating the financial self-sufficiency of the employed students, the survey data reveals that a majority of Indian students are able to meet their primary financial obligations through their local earnings. More than half of the respondents 51.7% (n = 92) reported that their income "fully" covers their basic living expenses, indicating a high degree of economic independence. 
Furthermore, 36% (n = 64) stated that their earnings "partially" cover their costs. Only a small segment of the working population, 10.7% (n = 19), indicated that their income is insufficient to cover basic expenses.  
 
4.3.4 The Monthly Income Distribution 
The largest segment of the students, comprising 34.3% (n = 61) of respondents, earns between 20,000 and 40,000 CZK per month. This is followed by 25.3% (n = 45) of the participants who fall into the 10,000 to 20,000 CZK bracket, A small sample of students has achieved higher financial standing; 15.7% (n = 28) earn between 40,000 and 60,000 CZK, and 11.8% (n = 21) have reached a high earning professional status with incomes ranging from 60,000 to 100,000 CZK. Conversely, only 
11.2% (n = 20) of the respondents earn below 10,000 CZK.  
