4.3.4 Job opportunities in Czech Republic vs. India 
The perception of the Czech labor market relative to the Indian market is highly positive among the surveyed students. On a scale of 1 to 5 (where 5 represents significantly better opportunities), 48.3% (n=86) of respondents rated job opportunities in the Czech Republic as a 4, with an additional 24.2% (n=43) giving it the highest rating of 5. According to 72.5% of the student, the Czech Republic has better career opportunities than India. A moderate stance was taken by 20.2% (n=36) of participants, while a small minority rated the opportunities lower, with only 2.8% (n=5) at a rating of 2 and 4.5% (n=8) at the lowest rating of 1.  
 
4.3.5 Expected Duration to Secure Employment 
In response to the question, "How many months do you expect it will take to land your first job after graduating?" most Indian students have a realistic but hopeful view of their entry into the Czech job market. About 46.1% (n=82) of respondents expect to secure their first job within 3 to 6 months of graduation. A notable 29.2% (n=52) are even more optimistic, predicting they will land a job in less than 3 months. Together, more than 75% of the students believe they will be employed within six months of finishing their studies. On the other hand, a smaller group of students expects a longer job search. Around 12.4% (n=22) anticipate it will take 6 to 12 months, and 7.3% (n=13) think it will take more than a year. These expectations show a general belief in the accessibility and effectiveness of the local job market for international graduates. 
 
4.4 Monthly Expenditure Analysis 
a)	Monthly Rent Expenditure: The cost of housing is the biggest fixed expense for Indian students. 46.6% (n=83) of respondents spend less than 10,000 CZK monthly on rent, while 35.4% (n=63) spend between 10,000 and 15,000 CZK. Together, 82% of students keep their rent under 15,000 CZK. A smaller group (16.3%, n=29) spends between 15,000 and 30,000 CZK, and only 1.7% (n=3) report rental costs above 30,000 CZK.
 
b)	Travel and Leisure Spending: Students show caution in their spending on leisure and travel. 71.9% (n=128) limit their monthly expenses in this area to under 10,000 CZK, focusing on essentials over fun activities. 18.0% (n=32) spend between 10,000 and 15,000 CZK for leisure and travel, while 9.6% (n=17) spend between 15,000 and 30,000 CZK. Very few (0.6%, n=1) spend more than 30,000 CZK.
 
c)	Monthly Food Expenditure: Food costs are a key part of the monthly budget. 56.7% (n=101) of respondents spend between 1,000 and 4,000 CZK on food each month, while 29.8% (n=53) spend between 4,000 and 7,000 CZK. Over 86% of students manage to keep their food costs under 7,000 CZK. A smaller group (10.7%, n=19) spends between 7,000 and 10,000 CZK, and only 2.8% (n=5) report food spending over 10,000 CZK monthly.
 
d)	Monthly Transport Expenditure: Transportation costs are typically well-managed. According to the survey, 73.0% (n=130) of respondents spend between 1,000 and 4,000 CZK each month on transport. This is followed by 19.1% (n=34) spending between 4,000 and 7,000 CZK. High transport costs are uncommon, with only 5.6% (n=10) spending between 7,000 and 10,000 CZK, and just 2.2% (n=4) spending more than 10,000 CZK, highlighting the affordability of Czech public transport for international students.
 
e)	Monthly Tuition and Materials Expenditure: Expenses for tuition and school supplies vary but are relatively low for most students. 59.0% (n=105) of respondents spend between 1,000 and 4,000 CZK monthly on tuition and materials, while 20.8% (n=37) spend between 4,000 and 7,000 CZK. Notably, 10.7% (n=19) spend above 10,000 CZK each month. The remaining 9.6% (n=17) report spending between 7,000 and 10,000 CZK.
 
f)	Managing living cost: Students rated their ability to manage living costs. 48.3% (n=86) rated their ability a 4 on a 5-point scale, while 20.2% (n=36) gave the highest rating of 5. Altogether, almost 69% of students feel confident in managing their finances in the local setting. A significant portion (28.1%, n=50) expressed a moderate level of confidence with a rating of 3, while only 3.4% (n=6) reported low confidence (ratings 1 and 2).
 
g)	Funding Source: Most respondents, 74.2% (n=132), rely on part-time jobs for their main income. This is closely followed by personal savings, cited by 57.3% (n=102) of students, and family support, which is vital for 48.9% (n=87) of students. Fewer students (12.9%, n=23) use loans, while 7.3% (n=13) benefit from scholarships.

  
 

