4.5. Important decision factors to choose Czech Republic as study destination 
 
To understand the specific drivers behind the choice of the Czech Republic, respondents were surveyed on the influence of affordability and the local labor market. 
a)	Czech Republic job market: On a scale of 1 to 5 (with 5 being extremely important), 53.9% (n=96) of respondents rated the importance of the job market as a 4, while 27.0% (n=48) assigned it the maximum rating of 5. Combined, over 80% of the participants indicated that the strength and accessibility of the Czech job market were critical factors in their initial decision-making process. Moderate importance was assigned by 13.5% (n=24) of students, while a negligible 5.6% (n=10) of the students considered it a minor or non-existent factor (ratings 1 and 2). 
 
b)	Affordability: While answering if economic accessibility is a primary driver for Indian students selecting the Czech Republic as their study destination. 70.8% (n=126) of respondents confirmed that affordability was a deciding factor in their choice. An additional 23.6% (n=42) indicated that it was "Maybe" a factor. Only a small minority (5.6%, n=10) stated that affordability did not play a role in their decision-making process. 
4.6 Overall Satisfaction and Recommendation 
The final measure of the success of the Czech Republic as an international education provider is operationalized by the subjective satisfaction rates of the sampled students along with their tendencies to recommend the destination to their own personal networks. This final part measures the overall experience of the Indian students, combining academic, financial and social aspects of the experience into a single satisfaction measure. 
 
a)	Overall Satisfaction with the Decision to Study in Czechia: On a scale of 1 to 5 (with 5 being "Highly Satisfied"), a substantial majority of 78.1% of respondents provided a positive rating of 4 or 5. Specifically, 46.6% (n=83) rated their satisfaction as a 4. Meanwhile, 31.5% (n=56) reported being highly satisfied with a rating of 5. In contrast, only a small 3.4% (n=6) expressed dissatisfaction with ratings of 1 and 2. Additionally, 18.5% (n=33) remained neutral.
 
b)	Willingness to Recommend to Other Indian Students: When asked if they would recommend the Czech Republic to other Indian students, 82% of the students responded positively. More than half of the respondents, 52.2% (n=93), selected "Definitely Yes." Meanwhile, 29.8% (n=53) indicated they would "Probably" recommend it. A small group, 14.0% (n=25), expressed uncertainty with "Maybe." Only a total of 3.9% (n=7) said they would not recommend the destination. 




 
