4.7.3 Comparison with Previous Research 
 
The findings of this research update prior research findings with regard to:  
 
•	Average Living Costs: Prior studies (Studyin.cz, 2023; AcadFly, 2024) indicated that the amount spent on living expenses per month for Indian Students is in the range of 15,000 - 20,000 CZK. The average expenditure recorded in this study (~31,700 CZK) is significantly higher than the previous research results. This difference in expenditure may be due to the impact of recent increases in costs due to inflation in the Czech Republic (primarily with regard to housing and food) and including tuition/material costs in an overall expenditure amount versus separate yearly estimated costs like in previous studies.
 
•	Motivation and Safety: According to the research by Haldorai et al. (2017), the cost of living is an important motivation for international students to study in the Czech Republic, but it is not the only reason. The results in this survey indicated that safety was also a large motivation for international students from India to study in the Czech Republic, and that was supported by the data collected from the students completing the survey as well as data reported by Live & Study (2025). 
•	Return on Investment: Findings from the research regarding degree level expenditures are similar to findings by Urbánek et al. (2012), which found students pursuing higher levels of education (Masters) are more willing to spend higher amounts than students pursuing lower levels of education on degree-level programs in Europe, and do so expecting to get a larger return on investments associated with education than from their counterparts with lower levels of education. 
•	The "Inflationary Leap" in Living Costs: 
According to historical data from Studyin.cz (2023) and AcadFly (2024), the monthly living expenses were estimated to be between 15,000 CZK to 20,000 CZK. However, according to your research, the new average is approximately 31,700 CZK, which is nearly doubling of expenses over the past three years. This is due to the effects of recent inflation on the cost of living, especially in the prices of housing and food, as well as the additional monthly expenses for "Tuition/Materials". 
•	The Safety-Expenditure Correlation: 
Although Live & Study (2025) identified safety as a major "pull factor" for international students, your research also shows a hidden expense associated with the perception of safety. Students who rate the overall campus safety as "Low/Moderate" have a much higher expenditure level (39,632 CZK), as opposed to those who rate it as "High" (31,431 CZK), (p = 0.007). This implies that international students who rate campus safety as low likely "buy" a sense of security by choosing to stay in a more exclusive, secured city center as opposed to the outskirts of the campus in a shared dorm setting. 



•	The Affordability Paradox: 
Haldorai et al. (2017) conducted research showing that cost was one of the most important reasons students choose to study in a certain country. Your study has shown that students who selected the Czech Republic because of its affordability spend more on rent (average of 11,854 CZK) compared to students who selected the Czech Republic as an option (average of 9,342 CZK) (p = 0.015). Your finding supports Studyin.cz’s (2023) assertion that the relative affordability of the Czech Republic compared to Western Europe enables Indian students to “upgrade” their standard of living while remaining within their total global budget. 
	• 	Analysis of Additional Statistically Significant Factors 
Apart from primary demographic factors, other factors were found to be statistically significant (p < 0.05) in determining financial behaviour. These factors include:  
•	Economic Lifestyle and Activity (p = 0.041): 
Students who engage in economic activities such as studying and working simultaneously exhibit greater total monthly expenditure. This shows that even though 74.2% of students in this study use their part-time income to sustain themselves, it is still reinvested in a better lifestyle.  
•	Job Market Perception and Settlement Investment (p = 0.035): 
Students who value the job market in the Czech Republic when initially determining where they will live will frequently spend more than other students. This would indicate that students view the Czech Republic as a long-term home and therefore are willing to make an investment in order to live there (settlement investment). 
•	Subjective Financial Literacy Impact (p = 0.031): 
Students who strongly agree with their ability to manage spending have significantly different levels of spending than those who do not. This is a confirmation that subjective financial confidence has a strong correlation with actual spending. 
•	Academic Level as a Success Predictor (p = 0.021): 
It is not only that master’s students spend more than their bachelor’s counterparts; they also have significantly higher incomes than the latter. This finding is consistent with that of Urbánek et al. (2012), which implies that academic levels have a positive impact on professional integration and the ability to become "independent-residents" in terms of spending.









4.7.4 Conclusion of Comparative Analysis: 
The research concludes that there has been a fundamental change in the socioeconomic profile of Indian students in the Czech Republic since 2023. This change from a "budget traveler" education model to a "settlement investment" model can be attributed to several critical factors. These factors are:
•	Academic Level as the Primary Economic Predictor: The level of study can be seen as the most important factor when discussing financial behavior. Master’s students are operating on a completely different economic level than bachelor’s students. This can be seen by the increased expenditure for master’s students (35,029 CZK compared to 28,233 CZK) and the increased income potential (p = 0.021).  
•	The Safety-Premium Effect: While the Czech Republic is considered a “safe haven.” (p <0.01), students’ perceptions of safety greatly affect their economics relative to others i.e., students’ with low safety leads to incurring large security premium. As an example, students’ secure private, central housing costs 39,632 CZK over more affordable options. 
•	The Affordability Paradox: The "Affordability Pull" does not lead to reduced overall spending. Rather, it allows students to improve their standard of living. Those who ranked affordability highly spend more on rent (11,854 CZK) than those who ranked it less highly (9,342 CZK).  
•	Professional Integration and Long-term Investment: The high employment levels of 86% indicate that students consider their time at the Czech Republic to be a long-term investment professionally. There was also a significant correlation between prioritizing jobs in the market and high current expenditure (p = 0.035). Therefore, this country is a long-term economically active student who will balance rising living costs with self-sufficiency levels of high and financially focused on building a career in Europe by strategic means. 

